{
  "analysis": "We are in /app with a compiled binary called mystery. We need to reverse-engineer its behavior and write a C source file mystery.c that compiles statically and behaves identically. First, inspect the file and run basic probes to understand its behavior.",
  "plan": "Run file/strings/size checks on /app/mystery, then execute it with no arguments and sample inputs to observe behavior. Also check if it reads stdin or arguments.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /app\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "file /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "strings -a /app/mystery | head -80\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "/app/mystery; echo \"exit=$?\"\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo hello | /app/mystery; echo \"exit=$?\"\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The mystery program ignores stdin and arguments, prints a fixed sequence of progress messages, exits 0, and writes image.ppm. The next step is to inspect the output file and try decompiling/disassembling the binary to reproduce the image exactly.",
  "plan": "Check whether image.ppm was created and inspect its header/size/content. Use available tools (objdump/readelf/nm) to examine the binary. Also search strings for format hints and any embedded constants.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /app/image.ppm 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "head -c 128 /app/image.ppm | xxd | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "wc -c /app/image.ppm 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which objdump readelf nm gdb python3 gcc gzip 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "readelf -h /app/mystery 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The binary is a statically linked ELF64 executable. It produced image.ppm of 5,362,624 bytes, which is too large for a binary P6 800x600 image (1,440,015 bytes), so it likely writes ASCII P3 PPM. We need to inspect the image format and reverse-engineer the rendering algorithm. Tools available: objdump, readelf, nm, gcc, gzip. No xxd/file/python3.",
  "plan": "Inspect image.ppm header and sample content using od. List relevant symbols with nm. Search strings for output/format hints. Disassemble main or entry-related functions with objdump to understand the rendering algorithm.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "head -c 300 /app/image.ppm | od -c | head -40\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "nm /app/mystery | grep -E ' main$| _start$| render| write| image| ppm| mandel| julia| fractal| fft| noise| perlin| ray' | head -50\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "strings -a /app/mystery | grep -Ei 'ppm|image|render|progress|done|ffmpeg|mandel|julia|fractal|noise|perlin|ray|trace|P3|P6|800|600|255' | head -100\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery | grep -A2 -B2 '<main>' | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The program is a simple static ray tracer. Symbols show main, ray_at, ray_create, write_image, allocate_image, and free_image. It writes an ASCII P3 800x600 255 PPM. The first pixels are near RGB (159,197,255), suggesting a sky gradient. Need to disassemble main and related functions to recover geometry and shading.",
  "plan": "Use nm to list all custom symbols, then disassemble main, write_image, ray_create, ray_at, and any sphere/scene/render-related functions. Capture enough assembly to reconstruct the algorithm.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "nm /app/mystery | grep -E ' [TtWw] ' | grep -iv '__\\|_libc\\|_dl\\|_IO\\|_math\\|_elf\\|_global\\|_frame\\|_Unwind\\|_dl_' | head -120\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d --start-address=0x401740 --stop-address=0x401ea0 /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d --start-address=0x401ea0 --stop-address=0x4020f0 /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d --start-address=0x4020f0 --stop-address=0x402400 /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The output was truncated and mixed main with sphere_intersect. We confirmed custom functions: main, ray_at, ray_create, write_image, allocate_image, free_image, and likely sphere_intersect. Need cleaner disassembly per function and the full custom symbol list.",
  "plan": "List all non-libc symbols in the 0x401xxx-0x403xxx range, then disassemble main separately to a file and view it in chunks. This will reveal the scene setup and render loop.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "nm /app/mystery | awk '$1>=\"0000000000401700\" && $1<=\"0000000000404000\" {print}'\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d --start-address=0x401740 --stop-address=0x401ea0 /app/mystery > /tmp/main.asm\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "wc -l /tmp/main.asm && sed -n '1,120p' /tmp/main.asm\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "sed -n '121,240p' /tmp/main.asm\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}
